text:
Steps for Applying Undetermined Coefficients

Identify the Form of \mathbf{b}(t): Determine the type of functions in the nonhomogeneous term \mathbf{b}(t). Typical forms include:

Polynomials: \mathbf{b}(t) = t^n \mathbf{c}
Exponentials: \mathbf{b}(t) = e^{rt} \mathbf{c}
Sines and Cosines: \mathbf{b}(t) = \sin(\theta t) \mathbf{c} or \cos(\theta t) \mathbf{c}

Use the Table to Choose a Guess for \mathbf{x}_p(t): Based on the form of \mathbf{b}(t), select a guess for \mathbf{x}_p(t) using the table below. If the guess overlaps with solutions to the homogeneous system, multiply by t as needed to create a new linearly independent solution.





Form of \mathbf{b}(t)


Guess for \mathbf{x}_p(t)


Additional Guess (if overlaps with homogeneous solution)




\mathbf{b}(t) = \mathbf{c}


\mathbf{x}_p = \mathbf{a}


\mathbf{x}_p = t \mathbf{a}




\mathbf{b}(t) = t \mathbf{c}


\mathbf{x}_p = \mathbf{a}_1 t + \mathbf{a}_0


\mathbf{x}_p = t^2 \mathbf{a}_1 + t \mathbf{a}_0




\mathbf{b}(t) = t^n \mathbf{c}


\mathbf{x}_p = \mathbf{a}_n t^n + \dots + \mathbf{a}_0


\mathbf{x}_p = t^{n+1} \mathbf{a}_n + \dots + t \mathbf{a}_0




\mathbf{b}(t) = e^{rt} \mathbf{c}


\mathbf{x}_p = e^{rt} \mathbf{a}


\mathbf{x}_p = t e^{rt} \mathbf{a}




\mathbf{b}(t) = t^n e^{rt} \mathbf{c}


\mathbf{x}_p = e^{rt} (\mathbf{a}_n t^n + \dots + \mathbf{a}_0)


\mathbf{x}_p = t^{n+1} e^{rt} (\mathbf{a}_n t^n + \dots + \mathbf{a}_0)




\mathbf{b}(t) = \cos(\theta t) \mathbf{c}


\mathbf{x}_p = \mathbf{a}_1 \cos(\theta t) + \mathbf{a}_2 \sin(\theta t)


\mathbf{x}_p = t (\mathbf{a}_1 \cos(\theta t) + \mathbf{a}_2 \sin(\theta t))




\mathbf{b}(t) = \sin(\theta t) \mathbf{c}


\mathbf{x}_p = \mathbf{a}_1 \cos(\theta t) + \mathbf{a}_2 \sin(\theta t)


\mathbf{x}_p = t (\mathbf{a}_1 \cos(\theta t) + \mathbf{a}_2 \sin(\theta t))




\mathbf{b}(t) = t^n \cos(\theta t) \mathbf{c}


\mathbf{x}_p = ( \mathbf{a}_n t^n + \dots + \mathbf{a}_0 ) \cos(\theta t)  + ( \mathbf{a}_{n+1} t^n + \dots + \mathbf{a}_1 ) \sin(\theta t)


\mathbf{x}_p = t^{n+1} \big[ ( \mathbf{a}_n t^n + \dots + \mathbf{a}_0 ) \cos(\theta t)  + ( \mathbf{a}_{n+1} t^n + \dots + \mathbf{a}_1 ) \sin(\theta t) \big]




\mathbf{b}(t) = t^n \sin(\theta t) \mathbf{c}


\mathbf{x}_p = ( \mathbf{a}_n t^n + \dots + \mathbf{a}_0 ) \cos(\theta t)  + ( \mathbf{a}_{n+1} t^n + \dots + \mathbf{a}_1 ) \sin(\theta t)


\mathbf{x}_p = t^{n+1} \big[ ( \mathbf{a}_n t^n + \dots + \mathbf{a}_0 ) \cos(\theta t)  + ( \mathbf{a}_{n+1} t^n + \dots + \mathbf{a}_1 ) \sin(\theta t) \big]




Substitute and Solve for Coefficients: Substitute \mathbf{x}_p(t) into the differential equation and solve for the unknown coefficients to ensure that the equation is satisfied.

Example
For a system:

\mathbf{x}' = A \mathbf{x} + e^{rt} \mathbf{c}

we might guess:

\mathbf{x}_p(t) = e^{rt} \mathbf{a}

If this guess overlaps with the homogeneous solution, we would use \mathbf{x}_p(t) = t e^{rt} \mathbf{a} instead. Substituting \mathbf{x}_p(t) into the system, we determine \mathbf{a} by equating terms.
